# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: harmony-day
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The **Cronulla riots** were a series of race riots in Sydney, Australia.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] They began in the beachside suburb of Cronulla on 11 December 2005, and over the following nights spread to additional suburbs.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] On the morning of Sunday, 11 December, a crowd gathered at Cronulla.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] By midday, approximately 5,000 people had gathered near the beach.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] As the gathering began attacking members of ethnic minorities, the police attempted to intervene.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Violence spread to neighbouring suburbs, where assaults occurred, including attacks on ambulances and police officers.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Two people were stabbed during these events, and travel warnings for Australia were briefly issued by some countries.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The riots were widely condemned by members of parliament, police, and local community leaders and residents.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A large police effort over subsequent months produced many arrests.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Some media were criticised, and well-known radio personality Alan Jones was formally censured and fined for his broadcasts during the week.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] New South Wales Police had been recording racial and ethnic tensions and incidents in and around Cronulla since October 2005.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] There is also a history of conflict between Cronulla locals and visiting beachgoers from the western suburbs ("Westies") with "bashings" (physical assault) common since the 1960s as part of a turf war between Westies and local surfers.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] There remains a great deal of debate as to whether previous racially charged attacks in the area like the Sydney gang rapes contributed to the tensions, or if the subsequent trials were used as justification for the attacks, despite many reporting otherwise.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The previous summer on Australia Day (26 January 2005), a non-racial riot occurred with around 2,000 to 3,000 young people in the Cronulla area engaged in "civil disobedience", at one stage hurling missiles at police attempting to control the crowd.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Just after 15:00 on Sunday, 4 December 2005, police were called to North Cronulla Beach following a report of an assault on two off-duty male surf lifesavers by four members of a group of eight men.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A verbal exchange had taken place after three lifesavers approached a group of four young men with a Lebanese background on Cronulla Beach, with both groups accusing the other of staring at them.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] One of the Australian Lebanese men reportedly responded to the accusations, "I'm allowed to; now fuck off and leave our beach", to which a lifesaver responded, "I come down here out of my own spare time to save you cunts from drowning".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The verbal exchange escalated with one Australian Lebanese youth attempting to defuse the situation.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Another Australian Lebanese youth then threw a punch, missing, prompting a pushing match that escalated into a fight.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] One of the lifesavers was badly hurt after falling and striking his head.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] One of the lifesavers later informed police that the four were part of a group of eight Australian Lebanese that had been on the beach most of the day and that there had been no problems with their prior behaviour.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Despite media reports to the contrary, no Middle Eastern men converged on the area and there were no more than the original eight present.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The events were reported widely across the Sydney media, particularly tabloid; also generating discussions on talkback radio.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] When a listener identified as "Berta" commented to shock jock Alan Jones of Sydney's 2GB Radio that she had heard "really derogatory remarks" aimed at Middle Eastern people, Jones interrupted stating "We don't have Anglo-Saxon kids out there raping women in Western Sydney".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Jones also broadcast and endorsed one listener's suggestion that bikie gangs be brought down to Cronulla railway station to deal with "Lebanese thugs" and that the event be televised, arguing that despite their notoriety bikie gangs do "a lot of good things".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] By Thursday, Jones had stirred significant discussion, and stated "I'm the person that's led this charge here.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] After the riots, Jones was found to have breached the Australian Communications and Media Authority (ACMA) Code of Conduct section 1.3(a), as his comments were "likely to encourage violence or brutality and to vilify people of Lebanese and Middle-Eastern backgrounds on the basis of ethnicity".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In December 2009, the NSW Administrative Decisions Tribunal found Jones and radio station 2GB guilty of vilifying Lebanese Muslims in earlier "Cronulla Riot" broadcasts.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Police were concerned about the repercussions of these events.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Later investigations revealed that over 270,000 individual SMS text messages were transmitted inciting a racially motivated confrontation at North Cronulla Beach the following Saturday.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Over the course of Sunday, 11 December 2005, approximately 5,000 people gathered in and around North Cronulla Beach.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Early in the morning, people began to gather and impromptu barbecues and "partying" took place.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] However at 12:59, a young man of "Middle Eastern appearance" was spotted on the beach and the crowds began "chanting stuff [and] yelling out things" before rushing him.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The man attempted to avoid the crowd by quickly entering "Northies", a local pub, but the crowd forcibly dragged him out and attacked him.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The police, having been in Cronulla since the early morning (including police helicopters and patrol boats), quickly intervened and resolved the situation.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A Cronulla High School teacher later claimed that the crowd had attacked the man after he had shouted "I'm going to blow youse all up".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At 13:30, two women verbally argued with a small group; the police arrived and both parties left.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] However, an hour later, they again met and a scuffle ensued.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At 13:45, another two boys from Bangladesh were surrounded by the crowd, and had bottles thrown at them, with the crowd repeatedly chanting "Fuck off Lebs!".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The two boys escaped by car, which was smashed, stomped on and pelted with objects along the way.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Chants and slogans such as "Fuck off Lebs!", "We grew here, you flew here", "Aussie Pride", "Fuck off wogs!", were repeated and displayed throughout the day by the crowd.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The crowd also attacked the police by throwing beer bottles.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Police vehicles were also prevented from entering the area.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Around 14:00 another three males were assaulted on the beach with the crowd throwing sausages and beer bottles at them.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Rumours had persisted throughout the day that an additional 600 people would arrive by train, mostly from the west of Cronulla, to join the crowds.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At approximately 15:00, "two young men of Middle Eastern appearance" arrived at Cronulla train station with the crowd outside chanting "Fuck off wogs!".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The two men (one of whom was a Russian-born Afghan) took refuge in the train.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] However, the mob entered the carriage and began assaulting them; a police officer entered the train and forcibly cleared the crowd, later being found to have used excessive force.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At 15:20, two separate assaults took place; one involved a crowd attacking a man of "Middle Eastern appearance" and throwing beer bottles.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In this case an officer intervened and removed the victim as they were both struck by the bottles.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A second assault took place outside a takeaway restaurant; three men were taken inside the restaurant as refuge and the diners already inside were moved towards the back.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The glass doors and windows were broken and those inside were moved outside without incident.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] By the end of the day, 26 people had been treated for injuries.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The 15:20 assault required the victim and the police officer to receive hospital treatment.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A total of 16 were arrested and charged with 42 offences including: malicious damage, assaulting a police officer, affray, offensive conduct, resisting arrest and numerous driving offences.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At 19:45, around 100 locals of Punchbowl (a suburb 20 kilometres [12 mi] to Cronulla's northwest) gathered together at the local Punchbowl Park.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Additional groups, armed with baseball bats, also gathered at The Promenade and Arncliffe Park.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Between 20:30 and 21:00, the groups formed a convoy of "more than 40 cars" and drove down to the beaches "to get revenge" with many of the cars ending up in Maroubra.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At 22:45, police were ordered "not to approach convoys of men of Middle Eastern appearance"; however car details and registration details were to be recorded.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A local of Maroubra reported that each of the cars that arrived was "full, you know, had four passengers".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The convoy was reportedly armed with bars and bats, knives, machetes and guns.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The group assaulted several people, knocking one unconscious and threatening another with rape, and damaged between 60 and 100 cars, setting at least one on fire in Arden Street, Coogee.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Police in riot gear moved to contain the violence and the crowds responded by throwing bricks and glass.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Residents reported that in some streets "every car" had had their windows smashed, with glass covering the streets.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Police also confiscated 40 iron bars and arrested 14 people.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At approximately 22:25, a 26-year-old mechanic Dan Gray was stabbed in the back three times and twice in the thigh with a 9.8 cm (3.9 in) blade.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The incident occurred outside Woolooware golf club when two cars carrying a group of males "described as being of Mediterranean or Middle Eastern appearance" approached the man and his friends.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Dan and his friends attempted to flee from the group, who were shouting "Get the Aussie dogs... get the Aussie sluts".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Dan was knocked to the ground and was repeatedly kicked in the head.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The attack ended when the knife snapped off in the victim's back.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] He was taken to hospital in a serious condition as the blade had narrowly missed his spine and lungs.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The getaway driver for the attack was arrested and held in jail for 9 months, after which he was paroled 5 months later for good behaviour.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A man named Jake Schofield was attacked by a group of four men of "Middle Eastern appearance", who beat him repeatedly, stabbing him twice and hitting him with a piece of concrete before stealing his wallet and keys.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The attack left him with a fractured eye socket and nose.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] All four assailants were arrested and charged.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A woman wearing a headscarf had her car stopped by a group of white males and was then abused and threatened by this group.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Additional smaller riots occurred on the following nights in the suburbs of Maroubra, Brighton-le-Sands and Cronulla.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Text messages similar to the earlier 270,000 inciting racial violence had also turned up in other states including Queensland, Victoria and Western Australia.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Approximately 2000 people gathered inside Lakemba Mosque with another 800 gathered outside the evening after the riot.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Sheikh Shady Alsuleiman spoke to the crowd and called for calm.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] However some were armed with Glock pistols which were displayed to the media.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] At least some of the people gathered were reported to have planned to go on to Maroubra; however the police blocked roads leading into Maroubra and 20 police cars surrounded the mosque.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The Uniting Church in Auburn, a predominantly Tongan congregation, was burned and those attending Christmas carols were abused and threatened.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] More than 30 Molotov cocktails were also confiscated by police.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] An additional seven people were injured including another police officer.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A husband and wife were taken to hospital after the wife was struck in the head and the husband tried to defend her, and another man was struck by a baseball bat and suffered a fractured forearm.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The far-right political party known as the Australia First Party claimed that 120 members and supporters attended the riots, and both members of the AFP and their youth wing, the Patriotic Youth League, were seen handing out anti-immigration leaflets and supplying alcohol there.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The now defunct Patriotic Youth League also played a part by distributing white power leaflets in the days prior to the riots, and held banners saying "Aussies fighting back" during the riots.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] By 19 July 2006, police had laid 285 charges against 104 people, 51 having been arrested as a result of the original Cronulla riot and 53 arrested from the retaliation riots.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] These persons were charged with, amongst other things: malicious damage, possession or use of a prohibited weapon, assaulting police, rioting, resisting arrest, threatening violence and affray.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Strike Force Enoggera was established on 13 December 2005, tasked with investigating the riots.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The strike force initially consisted of 28 members under the command of Superintendent Dennis Bray, but was increased to 100 officers on 20 January 2006.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Brian Wilshire, a 2GB radio host, stated the following weekend on air, "Many of them have parents who are first cousins whose parents are first cousins, the result of this inbreeding — the result of which is uneducationable [*sic*] people... and very low IQ", comments for which he later apologised.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] An anti-racism rally, attended by 2,000 people, was held in Bourke Street, Melbourne, Victoria.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Apologies for the riots at Cronulla were later issued on behalf of some local surf clubs, saying their members rejected racism and violence.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The gathering was justified as a protest against "ethnic gangs" with blame for the rioting and violence largely placed on alcohol and the agitation of far-right groups.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] During a press conference along with the Comanchero MC (which has a large number of Middle Eastern members), an apology from the Maroubra "Bra Boys" was also issued to leaders of the Islamic community.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Apologies from several others involved were also issued to Sydney's Lebanese community, though the earlier "protest" part of the day was still defended.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] She suggested that in recent years multiculturalism had begun to be derided with conservative politicians calling for one homogeneous, non-diverse culture, citing amongst others the "popularity and success" of Pauline Hanson and her One Nation Party.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In 2008, Australian portrait photographer Michel Lawrence published *All of Us*, a book containing photographs of people born in 200 other countries, but who were now living in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Lawrence said the *All of Us* project was wholly inspired by the Cronulla riots.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] "You watch this stuff on TV and you wonder why people are doing this – this is no way for a multicultural society to behave", said Lawrence.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The New South Wales parliament convened on 15 December to pass laws giving police new powers including: the ability to seize cars and mobile phones for up to seven days, close licensed premises and prohibit bringing alcohol into lockdown zones.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A new offence of "assault during a public disorder" was also introduced and both rioting and affray had their minimum sentences increased.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] New South Wales Premier Morris Iemma called the attacks "disgusting, cowardly behaviour" and condemned the rioters.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] He also called on the community leaders to use "their influence to get the hot heads to cool it".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Federal opposition leader Kim Beazley described the attacks as "simply criminal behaviour, that's all there is to it".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] One Nation NSW figure David Oldfield blamed the riots on the "failed social policy of multiculturalism" and called for an alternative assimilationist approach that highlights "the principles of unity given by a single national identity".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Many of the small businesses in and around Terrigal on the New South Wales Central Coast (two hours north of Cronulla) reported that a police lockdown of the beach caused business to drop to 10% of normal levels on a Saturday, with only 25% of Christmas shopping crowds turning up on the Sunday.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Tourism and hospitality workers in the area were laid off or had their hours cut.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The New South Wales state government announced a A$250,000 tourism campaign after authorities in Great Britain, Canada and Indonesia issued travel warnings to their citizens.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The Party for Freedom (PFF) planned to mark the tenth anniversary of the events with a rally on Saturday, 12 December 2015.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] PFF chairman Nicholas Folkes was refused permission in the Supreme Court of New South Wales "on the grounds it would stir up racial hatred".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In a separate case, the Federal Court of Australia ruled that no other person or groups could commemorate the anniversary.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The Federal ruling was in response to a joint application by Jamal Rifi, a prominent member of the Lebanese Muslim community in Australia, and the Sutherland Shire Council who applied for the Federal Court ruling.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In place of the rally a "halal-free" barbecue, attended by about 50, was held on Don Lucas Reserve near Wanda Beach.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A larger number of counter protesters in "the hundreds", including Antifa members, were also present.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A heavy police presence included the riot squad, mounted police and helicopter, and the two groups were mostly kept apart.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] Two anti-racism protesters were arrested.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The majority of the anti-racism protesters were escorted by police to Cronulla Railway station and onto trains headed towards the city of Sydney.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The Bondi shooting exacerbated older ethnic and religious tensions in the community.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In the immediate aftermath of the attack there was a threat of escalating violence with incitement circulated online focused on Cronulla, a beach near Bondi that was the epicentre of a previous anti-Arab and anti-Muslim race riot in 2005.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] In response to this, public assemblies were prohibited across the entire Sydney metro area for 14 days.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The targets of the calls for violent retaliation were the "Middle Eastern" and broader locally-described "wog" ethnic groups, referring to Lebanese Australians and other Eastern Mediterranean ethnic groups, the target of the previous mob violence.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The previous race riots, 20 years earlier, were triggered by local violent crimes committed by individual Lebanese Australian men in Sydney, in the context of tensions already heightened by terrorist attacks in Bali in 2002 targeting Australian tourists, and the September 11 attacks in 2001.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] A 20-year-old man appeared in court on charges of "using a carriage service to menace, harass, offend, and publicly threaten violence on grounds of race or religion", for attempting to incite retaliatory mob violence in response to the Bondi shooting.
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The article headline in *The Tenterfield Star* called him a "Muslim hater".
[src:harmony-day/2005-cronulla-riots] The 2016 film *Down Under* is set in the aftermath of the riots.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:harmony-day/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] As of 2020, Aboriginal Australians maintain a disproportionate level of exposure to the justice system and incarceration in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] One of the recommendations of the RCIADIC was that statistics and other information on Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal deaths in custody should be monitored nationally on an ongoing basis, by the Australian Institute of Criminology (AIC).
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] As Australian census and prison statistics include both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, the counts have included both groups, as Indigenous Australians.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The Australian Institute for Health and Welfare reports that the total Indigenous age specific deaths in 2018 were 164 per 100,000 for 25-34 year olds, and 368 for 35-44 year olds.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] These are the most relevant age groups for the current 12,000 Indigenous prisoners, with a median age of 32.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] In a group of 12,000 Indigenous 25-44 year olds, an average yearly death rate of around 32 per year occurs even outside prison.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The Indigenous death rate in prison is about 15 per year, or half of this.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] As of June 2021 the AIC had recorded 489 Indigenous deaths in custody since the Royal Commission (June 1991).
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The majority (65%) had been prison deaths with almost all the rest of the deaths in police custody or custody related operations.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The AIC's monitoring program reports Indigenous Australians have made up 18% of prison deaths and 20% of deaths in police custody or custody related operations in this time.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] This is well above their proportion in the general population that was 3.3% in the 2016 national census.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Although the majority of deaths occurring in prison custody have been of natural causes (58%), hanging deaths accounted for 32%, but the latter have shown a marked decrease in recent years.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Although they are greatly over-represented in the prisons, Indigenous prisoners have had a lower death rate than non-Indigenous prisoners since 2003.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] In 2020-21 the death rate for Indigenous prisoners was 0.09 per 100 compared to the non-Indigenous rate of 0.18.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Unfortunately, for technical reasons it is not possible to calculate death rates of Indigenous or non-Indigenous people in police custody or custody related operations.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Of deaths in police custody, the total between mid-1991 and mid-2016 was 146, with 47% attributed to accidental death (with most of these happening under police pursuit).
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] 21% were attributed to natural causes, with self-inflicted deaths accounting for 19%.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] There is, however, a number of cases in which calls have been made for greater scrutiny, as avoidable deaths, such as those of Ms Dhu, Tanya Day, David Dungay and Rebecca Maher.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Additional protests focusing on Aboriginal deaths in custody, accompanied by renewed media attention, were triggered by the murder of George Floyd in the US as part of the June 2020 protests in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Aboriginal deaths in custody and high incarceration rates were originally absent from the Australian Government's "Closing the Gap" strategy.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] As part of a 2018 pivot to a new phase, the Council of Australian Governments (COAG) drafted targets to reduce Aboriginal custody rates by 2028.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] It ran from 1987 to 1991, investigating the period between 1 January 1980 and 31 May 1989, producing its final report in April 1991.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The 1988 Australian Institute of Criminology publication, *Aboriginal Deaths in Custody*, says "The issue of Aboriginal deaths in prisons and holding cells is particularly complex".
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The report looks at the cases identified by RCIADIC by April 1988.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Criminologist Duncan Chappell, in his introduction to the report, writes that while the "problem of death in custody is by no means limited to Aboriginals", the "problem of Aboriginal deaths in custody is linked to fundamental issues which go beyond matters of criminal justice.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] It would be unfortunate if, by focusing on the criminal justice system, we lost sight of the profound social, cultural and economic problems which confront Aboriginal people".
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] At the time of RCIADIC, there was no ability to compare Aboriginal with non-Aboriginal deaths in custody because the information was not available from state and territory governments.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] At that time, the greatest number of Aboriginal deaths in custody had occurred in Western Australia and Queensland, half of the victims were under 28 years old, and the most common cause of death was hanging.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] More detailed analysis was needed, for instance into the different factors operating in police custody compared with correctional facilities.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] RCIADIC concluded that the deaths were not caused by deliberate killing by police and prison officers, but that "glaring deficiencies existed in the standard of care afforded to many of the deceased".
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Many other historical and social factors were considered, showing a complex network of reasons as to why Aboriginal people were imprisoned at a higher rate.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] A 2018 review by Deloitte commissioned in December 2017 by the then Indigenous Affairs Minister, Nigel Scullion, found that only 64% of the recommendations had been fully implemented.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] It reported that 14% were "mostly implemented", 16% were "partly implemented" and 6% not at all.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] It also found that monitoring of deaths in custody had decreased nationwide, and the quality of data on police custody was "an ongoing issue".
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Prison safety had increased, but more staff were needed for mental and other health issues of Aboriginal prisoners.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Regular in-cell checks, particularly in police watch houses, were still deficient in some jurisdictions.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people made up approximately 3.3% of the Australian population (798,365) in the 2016 Australian census.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] As of June 2018, Indigenous Australians aged 18 years and over were approximately 2% of the total adult population, while Indigenous prisoners accounted for 28% of the adult prison population, meaning that Indigenous adults are 15 times more likely to be imprisoned than non-Indigenous adults.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The rate of imprisonment of Indigenous Australians almost doubled between 1991 and 2018.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Indigenous youth are 26 times more likely to be placed in detention.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] According to the Australian Institute of Health and Welfare, in the June quarter of 2019 there was an average of 949 young people in detention per night: 90% of these were male, and 63% not yet sentenced.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Indigenous youths made up 53% of the number.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] In the four years preceding June 2019, there were no clear trends shown in any of the statistical measures.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The result of this in-depth enquiry was a report titled *Pathways to Justice – Inquiry into the Incarceration Rate of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Peoples*, which was received by the Attorney-General in December 2017 and tabled in Parliament on 28 March 2018.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The report made 13 recommendations, covering many aspects of the legal framework and police and justice procedures, including that non-payment of fines should not result in imprisonment.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Overall, the rate of Indigenous deaths in custody has reduced since 1991, as of June 2020 lower than the rate of death of non-Indigenous people, which the AIC attributes to improved care by police and corrective services.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] However the rate of imprisonment of Indigenous people has climbed steeply, which is related to the higher number of deaths when compared with the 10 years examined by the RCIDIAC (99 in 10 years, compared with about 437 in 29 years).
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Non-Indigenous people have died in custody in greater numbers and at a higher rate than Indigenous people, since 1991; however, with the much higher numbers of imprisonment of Indigenous people, there are more deaths as a proportion of their total population.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Attorney-General for Western Australia, John Quigley, said in June 2020 that there was "systematic discrimination" against Indigenous people in the Western Australian justice system.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Statistically, Indigenous people were far more likely to be stopped and questioned by police than non-Indigenous, more likely to be charged if arrested by police and less likely to get bail.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Imprisonment of Indigenous people in WA was 4.1 per cent, compared with 2.6 nationally.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The number of Indigenous adults going to prison, and young people being held in detention was still increasing, although the rate of imprisonment had slowed.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] He said that legislative reforms were being planned.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] WA has a higher number of Aboriginal deaths in custody since 1991 than any other state or territory.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] On 17 June 2020 reforms to the legislation relating to jail sentences for unpaid fines, long a bone of contention, spurred on by the death of Ms Dhu in 2014 and finally introduced into Parliament in September 2019, was passed in WA.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Between 1 July 2018 and 30 June 2019, 430 people spent time in custody for unpaid fines.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Under the new legislation, most fine defaulters will do community service if they fail to pay, with imprisonment a last resort, by order of a magistrate only.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The change was recommended by RCIADIC in 1991.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] Data covering the period 2014–2024 showed that WA had the highest rate of Indigenous deaths in custody per capita.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] The Police Association of South Australia proposed a change to the legal definition in June 2020.
[src:harmony-day/aboriginal-deaths-in-custody] However this idea was opposed by the Aboriginal Legal Rights Movement (ALRM) and the opposition (Labor) Aboriginal Affairs spokesperson Kyam Maher, who said that it was important to keep consistency in the statistics for comparison purposes.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles was born in Melbourne on 31 July 1973.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] His mother was born in the United Kingdom, making him a British citizen by descent; he renounced his dual citizenship before standing for parliament in 2013.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles attended high school at Scotch College, Melbourne.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles has a Bachelor of Arts and Laws from the University of Melbourne.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Before entering parliament, he was a principal solicitor for Slater and Gordon and as a senior associate at Holding Redlich lawyers and consultants.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] He acted as a solicitor for refugees stranded aboard the MV *Tampa*.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles also worked as a senior advisor for the Bracks and Brumby Governments in Victoria.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] He was secretary of the Socialist Left in Victoria.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles was elected to parliament at the 2013 federal election, replacing the retiring Harry Jenkins in the Division of Scullin.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] He immediately took up a position as Labor's cities taskforce and has engaged in an Australia-wide cities listening tour.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] He is co-chair of Parliamentary friends of Amnesty International, and the deputy chair of the Parliament's Northern Europe group of its IPU members.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] In 2016 he was elevated to the position of the Shadow Assistant Minister for Schools.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] In 2019 he became a member of Labor's Shadow Ministry.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] His portfolios included: Multicultural Affairs, Cities and Urban Infrastructure.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] He also served as the Shadow Minister Assisting for Immigration and Citizenship.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] In this role Giles led Labor's campaign to stop the Morrison Government's attempts to privatise Australia's visa system.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] He was also responsible for Labor's ‘reboot’ with multicultural communities, including the establishment of a Multicultural Caucus Committee to inform future policy development.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Following the 2022 federal election, Giles was appointed as Minister for Immigration, Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs in the Albanese ministry.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] As Immigration Minister, Giles issued "Ministerial Direction 99" in early 2023 to the Department of Home Affairs and Administrative Appeals Tribunal (AAT), which tightened the criteria for deporting non-citizen residents by focusing on their community ties and duration of time spent in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] This policy change had come in response to the New Zealand Government's objection to the large number of New Zealand criminals being deported from Australia despite their limited connection to New Zealand.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] On 7 June 2024, Giles issued Ministerial Direction 110 which prioritised community safety as a criterion for deporting non-citizens.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Under the new criteria, Giles also cancelled the visas of 40 non-citizens, citing national interest.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles has two children and lives with his wife, Dr Jillian Constable.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] Giles lives outside the electorate of Scullin, in Clifton Hill, according to his Parliamentary Register of Interests.
[src:harmony-day/andrew-giles] In the 1990s, he played guitar in an indie rock band called Ether, along with James Cecil, who went on to play in bands such as Architecture in Helsinki.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] European racism was spread to the Americas by the Europeans, who had used slaves as unpaid workers, but establishment views were questioned when they were applied to indigenous peoples.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In December 1511, Antonio de Montesinos, a Dominican friar, was the first European to rebuke openly the Spanish authorities and administrators of Hispaniola for their "cruelty and tyranny" in dealing with the American natives and those forced to labor as slaves.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] King Ferdinand enacted the *Laws of Burgos* and *Valladolid* in response.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Enforcement was lax, and the New Laws of 1542 have to be made to take a stronger line.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Afterward, their Christian conversion effort gained momentum along social rights, while leaving the same status recognition unanswered for Africans of Black Race, and legal social racism prevailed towards the Indians or Asians.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] These issues gradually permeated to the lower social levels, where they were a reality lived by men and women of different races from the European racial majority.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In 1688, German immigrants to the Province of Pennsylvania issued an anti-slavery petition opposing slavery in the colony.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] After being set aside and forgotten, it was rediscovered by American abolitionists in 1844, misplaced around the 1940s, and once more rediscovered in March 2005.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Prior to the American Revolution, a small group of Quakers, including John Woolman and Anthony Benezet, persuaded many fellow Quakers to emancipate their slaves, divest from the Atlantic slave trade and create unified Quaker policies against slavery.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] This afforded the religious denomination a measure of moral authority to help begin the American abolitionist movement.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Woolman died of smallpox in England in 1775, shortly after crossing the Atlantic to spread his anti-slavery message to the Quakers of the British Isles.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] During and after the American Revolution, Quaker ministrations and preachings against slavery began to spread beyond their denomination.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In 1783, 300 Quakers, chiefly from London, presented the British Parliament with a petition against the Britain's involvement in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In 1785, English abolitionist Thomas Clarkson, studying at Cambridge, and in the course of writing an essay in Latin (*Anne liceat invitos in servitutem dare* (Is it lawful to enslave the unconsenting?), read the works of Benezet, and began a lifelong effort to abolish the British slave trade.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In 1787, British abolitionists formed the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade, a small nondenominational group that could lobby more successfully by incorporating Anglicans, who, unlike the Quakers, could lawfully sit in Parliament.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The twelve founding members included nine Quakers and three pioneering Anglicans: Granville Sharp, Thomas Clarkson, and William Wilberforce – all evangelical Christians.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Later successes in opposing racism were won by the abolitionist movement in England and in the United States.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Though many Abolitionists did not regard blacks or mulattos as equal to whites, they did, in general, believe in freedom and often even equality of treatment for all people.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Due to resistance in the Southern United States and a general collapse of idealism in the North, Reconstruction ended, giving way to the nadir of American race relations.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The period from about 1890 to 1920 saw the re-establishment of Jim Crow laws.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] President Woodrow Wilson, who regarded Reconstruction as a disaster, segregated the federal government.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The Ku Klux Klan grew to its greatest peak of popularity and strength; the success of D.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Griffith's *The Birth of a Nation* played a major part in this member increase.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In 1911 the First Universal Races Congress met in London, at which distinguished speakers from many countries for four days discussed race problems and ways to improve interracial relations.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Karl Marx was supportive of the Union during the American Civil War and advocated more radical abolitionist measures with his *Address of the International Working Men's Association* to Abraham Lincoln in 1864.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Lincoln would in return commend the International Working Men's Association for their support and declared that the defeat of the South would be a victory for all of humanity.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The Russian Revolution was perceived as a rupture with imperialism for various civil rights and decolonization struggles and providing a space for oppressed groups across the world.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] This was given further credence with the Soviet Union supporting many anti-colonial third world movements with financial funds against European colonial powers.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In his work, *The Socialist Revolution and the Rights of Nation to Self-Determinism*, Vladimir Lenin wrote that socialism would enforce the complete equality of all nations and "give effect to the right of oppressed nations to self-determination".
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Lenin would make anti-imperialism a tenet of Marxist ideology and coordinate revolutions through the Comintern.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Marxist theorist Leon Trotsky had advocated for national self-determination for the black population in South Africa.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Through the 1930s, the first viable black trade unions in Transvaal, South Africa were established by Trotskyists.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Modern left-wing commentators have argued that capitalism promotes racism alongside culture wars over issues such as immigration and representation of ethnic minorities whilst refusing to address economic inequalities.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Socialist groups have also been closely aligned with a number of anti-racist organizations such as Love Music Hate Racism, Stand Up to Racism, Anti-Nazi League and Unite Against Fascism.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] A number of socialist activists and organisations have linked reparations for slavery and colonisation with a wider set of anti-capitalist demands to reconfigure the world economy.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In this view, a transition to a world socialist economy would redress reparations and upskill the quality of education, healthcare and living standards of marginalised communities and working classes.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Friedrich Tiedemann was one of the first people to scientifically contest racism.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] German ethnographer Adolf Bastian promoted the idea known as "psychic unity of mankind", the belief in a universal mental framework present in all humans regardless of race.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Rudolf Virchow, an early biological anthropologist criticized Ernst Haeckel's classification of humanity into "higher and lower races".
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The two authors influenced American anthropologist Franz Boas who promoted the idea that differences in behavior between human populations are purely cultural rather than determined by biological differences.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Later anthropologists like Ashley Montague, Ruth Benedict, Marcel Mauss, Bronisław Malinowski, Pierre Clastres, and Claude Lévi-Strauss continued to focus on culture and reject racial models of differences in human behavior.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The Jena Declaration, published in 2019 by the German Zoological Society, rejects the idea of human "races" and distances itself from the racial theories of Ernst Haeckel and other 20th century scientists.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] It claims that genetic variation between human populations is smaller than within them, demonstrating that the biological concept of "races" is invalid.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The statement highlights that there are no specific genes or genetic markers that match with conventional racial categorizations.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] It also indicates that the idea of "races" is based on racism rather than any scientific factuality.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] After the end of seclusion in the 1850s, Japan signed unequal treaties, the so-called Ansei Treaties, but soon came to demand equal status with the Western powers.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Correcting that inequality became the most urgent international issue of the Meiji government.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In that context, the Japanese delegation to the 1919 Paris Peace Conference proposed the clause in the Covenant of the League of Nations.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] After Makino's speech, Lord Cecil stated that the Japanese proposal was a very controversial one and he suggested that perhaps the matter was so controversial that it should not be discussed at all.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Greek Prime Minister Eleftherios Venizelos also suggested that a clause banning religious discrimination should also be removed since that was also a very controversial matter.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] That led to objections from a Portuguese diplomat, who stated that his country had never signed a treaty before that did not mention God, which caused Cecil to remark perhaps this time, they would all just have to a take a chance of avoiding the wrath of the Almighty by not mentioning Him.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Australian Prime Minister Billy Hughes clarified his opposition and announced at a meeting that "ninety-five out of one hundred Australians rejected the very idea of equality.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Hughes had entered politics as a trade unionist and, like most others in the working class, was very strongly opposed to Asian immigration to Australia.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The Chinese delegation, which was otherwise at daggers drawn with the Japanese over the question of the former German colony of Qingdao and the rest of the German concessions in Shandong Province, also said that it would support the clause.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] One contemporary Chinese diplomat said the Shandong question was far more important to his government than the clause.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] British Prime Minister David Lloyd George found himself in an awkward situation since Britain had signed an alliance with Japan in 1902, but he also wanted to hold the British Empire's delegation together.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Although the proposal received a majority (11 out of 16) of votes, the proposal was still problematic for the segregationist US President Woodrow Wilson, who needed the votes of segregationist Southern Democrats to succeed in getting the votes needed for the US Senate to ratify the treaty.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Strong opposition from the British Empire delegation gave him a pretext to reject the proposal.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Hughes and Joseph Cook vigorously opposed it as it undermined the White Australia policy.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Opposition to racism revived in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] At that time, anthropologists such as Franz Boas, Ruth Benedict, Margaret Mead, and Ashley Montagu argued for the equality of humans across races and cultures.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Eleanor Roosevelt was a very visible advocate for minority rights during this period.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-capitalist organizations like the Industrial Workers of the World, which gained popularity during 1905–1926, were explicitly egalitarian.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] In the 1940s Springfield, Massachusetts, invoked The Springfield Plan to include all persons in the community.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Beginning with the Harlem Renaissance and continuing into the 1960s, many African-American writers argued forcefully against racism.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The struggles against racial segregation in the United States and South African apartheid including Sharpeville massacre saw increased articulation of ideas opposed to racism of all kinds.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] During the Civil Rights Movement, Jim Crow laws were repealed in the South and blacks finally re-won the right to vote in Southern states.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Martin Luther King Jr. was an influential force, and his "I Have a Dream" speech is a condensation of his egalitarian ideology.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Mass mobilization around the Black Lives Matter movement have sparked a renewed interest in anti-racism in the U.S.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Mass movement organizing has also been accompanied by academic efforts to foreground research regarding anti-racism in politics, criminal justice reform, inclusion in higher education, and workplace anti-racism.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-racism has been argued to include opposition to antisemitism and anti-White racism.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-racists focused on institutional and structural racism have fought, including through nonviolent resistance and legislative campaigns, for anti-discrimination legislation, as exemplified by the US Civil Rights Act, 1964 and UK Race Relations Act 1965.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The anti-apartheid movement in the 1980s campaigned globally for an end to racial discrimination in South Africa.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Groups targeted by racism have built political but also cultural movements to demand respect and recognition and revalorise oppressed peoples.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Examples include Cultural Zionism, the Harlem Renaissance, negritude, the Black Arts Movement, and the Black pride/Black power and Chicano power movements.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Proponents of anti-racism claim that microaggressions can lead to many negative consequences in a work environment, learning environment, and to their overall sense of self-worth.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-racism work aims to combat microaggressions and help to break systemic racism by focusing on actions against discrimination and oppression.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Standing up against discrimination can be an overwhelming task for people of color who have been previously targeted.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-racists claim that microinterventions can be a tool used to act against racial discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Microintervention strategies aim to provide the tools needed to confront and educate racial oppressors.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Specific tactics include: revealing the hidden biases or agendas behind acts of discrimination, interrupting and challenging oppressive language, educating offenders, and connecting with other allies and community members to act against discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The theory is that these microinterventions allow the oppressor to see the impact of their words, and provide a space for an educational dialogue about how their actions can oppress people marginalized groups.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Microaggressions can be conscious acts where the perpetrator is aware of the offense they are causing, or hidden and metacommunicated without the perpetrator's awareness.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Regardless of whether microaggressions are conscious or unconscious behaviors, the first anti-racist intervention is to name the ways it is harmful for a person of color.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Calling out an act of discrimination can be empowering because it provides language for people of color to bring awareness to their lived experiences and justifies internal feelings of discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-racist strategies also include confronting the racial microaggression by outwardly challenging and disagreeing against the microaggression that harms a person of color.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Microinterventions such as a verbal expression of "I don't want to hear that talk" and physical movements of disapproval are ways to confront microaggressions.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Microinterventions are not used to attack others about their biases, but instead they are used to allow the space for an educational dialogue.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Educating a perpetrator on their biases can open up a discussion about how the intention of a comment or action can have a damaging impact.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] For example, phrases such as "I know you meant that joke to be funny, but that stereotype really hurt me" can educate a person on the difference between what was intended and how it is harmful to a person of color.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Anti-racist micro intervention strategies give the tools for people of color, white allies, and bystanders to combat against microaggressions and acts of discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Another strategy involves fostering an inclusive environment by consistently promoting cultural safety, cultural humility, and narrative humility.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Cultural safety encourages individuals to examine their own identities and attitudes, creating spaces that are emotionally, socially, and physically safe for everyone while affirming the unique identities and needs of individuals from diverse cultural backgrounds.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Cultural humility complements this by emphasizing self-reflection, co-learning, and collaboration with community members, underscoring the value of shared growth.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Narrative humility further enhances this approach by encouraging individuals to listen attentively to others' stories, reflect on their roles within those narratives, and remain open to perspectives that challenge their own.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Together, these approaches work to dismantle systemic inequities and cultivate environments grounded in respect, shared understanding, and active participation.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Egalitarianism has been a catalyst for feminist, anti-war, and anti-imperialist movements.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Henry David Thoreau's opposition to the Mexican–American War, for example, was based in part on his fear that the U.S. was using the war as an excuse to expand slavery into new territories.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Thoreau's response was chronicled in his famous essay "Civil Disobedience", which in turn helped ignite Mahatma Gandhi's successful leadership of the Indian independence movement.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Gandhi's example in turn inspired the American civil rights movement.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Some of these uses have been controversial.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Critics in the United Kingdom, such as Peter Hain, stated that in Zimbabwe, Robert Mugabe had used anti-racist rhetoric to promote land distribution, whereby privately held land was taken from white farmers and distributed to black Africans (see: Land reform in Zimbabwe).
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] Cultural critic Fredrik deBoer placed blame on "idea-generating" individuals and institutions for the perceived failures of BLM as a social movement.
[src:harmony-day/anti-racism] The phrase was spotted on billboards near Birmingham, Alabama in 2014, and it was also spotted on billboards in Harrison, Arkansas in 2013.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] The **Australian Fabians** (also known as the **Australian Fabian Society**) is an Australian independent left-leaning think tank that was established in 1947.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] The Australian Fabians has close ties with the Australian Labor Party (ALP) and the Australian labour movement.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] Many past ALP prime ministers, federal ministers and state premiers were active members of the Australian Fabians while in office.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] The role of patron of the Australian Fabians is currently vacant and has been held by media and social commentator and feminist Eva Cox and former Australian prime minister, the late Gough Whitlam.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] The Australian Fabians have had a significant influence on public policy development in Australia since the Second World War, with many of its members having held influential political offices in Australian governments.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] The Australian members retained their membership for ten years until the Adelaide branch was wound up in 1902.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] Another South Australian branch had an inaugural dinner 1938, but the society in its current form wasn't founded until 1947.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] During the 1960s, the Victorian branch was closely aligned with the Participants grouping within the Victorian Labor Party, "who became the centre of organised support for Whitlam and opposition to the hard-left dominated Victorian Central Executive".
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] The Victorian Labor Party at the time was run by the historic left grouping, while Whitlam and other states were involved with the historic right grouping.
[src:harmony-day/australian-fabian-society] Penny Wong frequently speaks to and writes for the Australian Fabians.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The **Australian Greens**, commonly referred to simply as **the Greens**, are a left-wing green Australian political party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] As of 2025, the Greens are the third-largest political party in Australia by vote and the fourth-largest by elected representation.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Following the 2025 Australian federal election, Larissa Waters serves as Leader of the Greens and Mehreen Faruqi serves as deputy leader.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party was formed in 1992 as a confederation of eight state and territorial parties.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In their early years, the party was largely built around the personality of well-known Tasmanian politician Bob Brown, before expanding its representation substantially in the early part of the 21st century.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party cites four core values as its ideology, namely ecological sustainability, social justice, grassroots democracy, and peace and non-violence.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party's origins can be traced to the early environmental movement in Australia, the Franklin Dam controversy, the Green bans, and the nuclear disarmament movement.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party began with the United Tasmania Group, one of the first green parties in the world.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] At the 2025 federal election, the Greens lost 3 of their previous 4 representatives in the House of Representatives and retained all 11 of their senate seats.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Co-ordination between environmentalist groups occurred in the 1980s with various significant protests.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Key people involved in these campaigns included Bob Brown and Christine Milne, who went on to contest and win seats in the Parliament of Tasmania and eventually form the Tasmanian Greens.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Both Brown and Milne subsequently became leaders of the federal party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The formation of the federal party in 1992 brought together over a dozen green groups, from state and local organisations, some of which had existed for 20 years.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Following the formation of the national party in 1992, regional emphasis variations remained within the Greens, with members of the "industrial left" remaining a presence in the New South Wales branch.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Brown resigned from the Tasmanian Parliament in 1993, and in 1996 he was elected as a senator for Tasmania, the first elected as an Australian Greens candidate.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Initially, the most successful Greens group during this period was The Greens (WA), which was still a separate organisation from the Australian Greens at the time.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Vallentine was succeeded by Christabel Chamarette in 1992, and she was joined by Dee Margetts in 1993.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] However, Chamarette was defeated in the 1996 federal election.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Margetts lost her seat in the 1998 federal election, leaving Brown as the sole Australian Greens senator.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In the 2001 federal election, Brown was re-elected as a senator for Tasmania, and a second Greens senator, Kerry Nettle, was elected in New South Wales.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens opposed the Howard government's Pacific Solution of offshore processing for asylum seekers, and opposed the bipartisan offers of support to ANZUS and the Afghanistan War by the government and Beazley Opposition in the aftermath of the September 11 attacks.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party described the Afghanistan commitment in particular as "warmongering".
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Brown and Nettle's performance in the Senate increased voter support for the party, as it showcased that the Greens were not deep ecologists nor a single-issue environmentalist organisation, thus granting approval from disaffected Labor voters.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On 19 October 2002, the Greens won a House of Representatives seat for the first time when Michael Organ won the Cunningham by-election, triggered by the resignation of Labor member Stephen Martin.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In the 2004 federal election, the Australian Greens fielded candidates in every House of Representatives seat in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens' primary vote rose by 2.3% to 7.2%.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] This won them two additional Senate seats, taken by Christine Milne in Tasmania and Rachel Siewert in Western Australia, bringing the total to four.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In New South Wales, the Greens ran John Kaye as their lead Senate candidate but were unsuccessful due to unfavourable preference flows, and Organ lost his seat to Labor's Sharon Bird.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] At the 2004 election, the Australian Greens replaced the Australian Democrats as the largest third party in elections, a title that they have held since.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens increased their national vote by 1.38 points to 9.04% at the 2007 federal election, with the election of South Australian senator Sarah Hanson-Young taking the number of Greens senators to five.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Senators Bob Brown (Tas) and Kerry Nettle (NSW) were up for re-election, Brown was re-elected, but Nettle was unsuccessful, becoming the only Australian Greens senator to lose their seat despite increasing her vote from 2001.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In November 2008, Senator Christine Milne was elected deputy leader in a ballot contested against Senator Rachel Siewert.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In 2009, the Greens and the Liberal Party voted to defeat Labor's emission trading scheme legislation after failed negotiations for an emissions cut target.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The 2010 federal election marked a high point for the Greens electorally, with the party receiving its largest vote to date and sharing the balance of power.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens received a four percent swing to finish with 13 percent of the vote in the Senate.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens won a seat in each of the six states at the election, bringing the party to a total of nine senators from July 2011, holding the balance of power in the Senate.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The new senators were Lee Rhiannon in New South Wales, Richard Di Natale in Victoria, Larissa Waters in Queensland, Rachel Siewert in Western Australia, Penny Wright in South Australia and Christine Milne in Tasmania.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Incumbents Scott Ludlam in Western Australia, Sarah Hanson-Young in South Australia and Bob Brown in Tasmania were not due for re-election.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens also won their first House of Representatives seat at a general election, the seat of Melbourne with candidate Adam Bandt, who was a crossbencher in the first hung parliament since the 1940 federal election.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Almost two weeks after the election, the Greens agreed to support a Gillard Labor minority government on confidence and supply votes.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Labor was returned to government with the additional support of three independent crossbenchers.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Prior to the 2010 federal election, the Electrical Trades Union's Victorian branch donated $325,000 to the Greens' Victorian campaign – the largest political donation ever directed to the Party up to that time.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Key issues remained to be negotiated between the Government and the cross-benches, including compensation arrangements for households and businesses, the carbon price level, the emissions reduction target and whether or not to include fuel in the price.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In April 2012, Bob stepped down as leader of the Australian Greens, and retired from the Senate in June 2012.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Christine Milne led the Australian Greens through the remainder of the minority parliament, after being elected unopposed.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] At the 2013 federal election, the House of Representatives (lower house) primary vote was 8.7 percent (−3.1) with the Senate (upper house) primary vote at 8.7 percent (−4.5).
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Despite receiving a decline in votes, the Greens representation in the parliament increased.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Adam Bandt retained his Melbourne seat with a primary vote of 42.6 percent (+7.0) and a two-candidate preferred vote of 55.3 percent (−0.6).
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens won four Senate positions, increasing their Senate representation from nine to ten senators.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] At the 2014 Australian Senate special election in Western Australia, the Greens won in excess of a quota with the primary vote increasing from 9.5 to 15.6 percent, re-electing Scott Ludlam.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In December 2015, the Greens struck a deal with the Coalition government, passing a law requiring multinational private companies with a turnover over $200 million to disclose their tax arrangements.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] This law also made it mandatory for multinational companies with a *global* turnover of $1 billion or more to have to prepare "general purpose" financial statements, which disclose greater tax details than previously occurred in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The following year the Coalition government and the Greens agreed on a permanent 15% tax rate for backpackers, in exchange for a $100 million funding boost to environmental stewardship not-for-profit Landcare.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Christine Milne stepped down from the leadership of the Australian Greens on 6 May 2015.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Di Natale was elected unopposed as parliamentary leader of the Greens party room on 6 May 2015 following the resignation of Christine Milne from the position.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] At the 2016 federal election, the House of Representatives (lower house) primary vote increased to 10.23 percent (+1.58) but decreased in the Senate (upper house), with primary vote at 8.65 percent (−0.58).
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Adam Bandt was elected to a third term in his Melbourne seat with a primary vote of 43.75 percent (+1.13) and a two-candidate preferred vote of 68.48 percent (+13.21).
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Despite a campaign focus on winning additional seats in the lower house, The Greens failed to win any lower house contests.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens also lost one Senate position in South Australia, decreasing their Senate representation from ten to nine senators, to a total of ten Green members in the Parliament of Australia.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The result was seen as disappointing, and caused internal divisions to flare up, with former Federal Leader Bob Brown calling upon Senator Lee Rhiannon to resign, citing the "need for renewal".
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In 2017, Greens Senators Scott Ludlam and Larissa Waters were forced to resign during 2017–18 Australian parliamentary eligibility crisis after it was found that Ludlam had dual Australian–New Zealand citizenship and Waters had dual citizenship with Canada.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Subsequently, Adam Bandt and Rachel Siewert were named as temporary co-deputy leaders until the arrival of Ludlam and Waters' replacements in Canberra.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] At the 2019 federal election, the Australian Greens received a primary vote of 10.4% in the House of Representatives, with a federal swing of +0.2%.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party's highest vote was captured in the Australian Capital Territory (16.8%), followed by Victoria (11.9%), Western Australia (11.6%), Queensland (10.3%), Northern Territory (10.2%), Tasmania (10.1%), South Australia (9.6%) and New South Wales (8.7%).
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party retained the federal electorate of Melbourne with Adam Bandt sitting at a 71.8% two-party preferred vote.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] All six Greens senators up for re-election retained their seats, including Senators Mehreen Faruqi, Janet Rice, Larissa Waters, Sarah Hanson-Young, Jordon Steele-John and Nick McKim.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Three key seats were targeted by the Greens in Victoria, including Kooyong, Higgins and Macnamara.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Prominent barrister Julian Burnside, who stood for Kooyong, came close to unseating treasurer and deputy Liberal leader Josh Frydenberg, falling short by 5.7% in the two-party preferred vote.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Greens candidate Jason Ball, for the Division of Higgins, failed to enter the two-party preferred vote, despite optimism within the Greens and a diminishing Liberal vote.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In Macnamara (formerly Melbourne Ports), a three-way contest emerged between the Liberals, Labor and Greens.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Greens candidate Steph Hodgins-May had come within a few hundred votes in 2016 of taking the seat, however, redistributions in the electorate for the 2019 election were unfavourable for the Greens' vote, and the party's final vote sat at 24.2%.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On 3 February 2020, Di Natale resigned as leader of the Greens and announced his intention to resign from the Senate.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On 4 February, Adam Bandt was elected unopposed as parliamentary leader of the Australia Greens party room.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens' strategy for the 2022 federal election involved targeting nine key seats, including the previously Labor-held seats of Macnamara, Griffith, Richmond, Wills, and Canberra, and four previously Liberal-held seats of Kooyong, Brisbane, Ryan and Higgins.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Analysis of vote trends suggested the party succeeded in picking up former votes of both Labor and the Liberal Party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party were unsuccessful in picking up the seat of Richmond with their high-profile candidate Mandy Nolan.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On 6 February 2023, Victorian Greens senator Lidia Thorpe announced that she would resign from the Greens to become an independent senator, over disagreements concerning the proposed Indigenous Voice to Parliament.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In mid-March 2024, the Greens announced they would introduce legislation seeking to break the dominance of the two supermarket giants Woolworths Group and Coles Group by forcing them to sell some of their operations.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] While the Albanese government did not support the bill, it found support from the centre-right National Party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens lost party leader Adam Bandt in the seat of Melbourne, Stephen Bates in the seat of Brisbane, and Max Chandler-Mather in the seat of Griffith in the 2025 federal election, with Labor taking all three seats in a landslide victory.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] When Bandt conceded on 8 May 2025 Tasmanian Greens senator Nick McKim as party whip became acting leader until the planned leadership meeting.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Queensland Senator Larissa Waters was elected unopposed as party leader on 15 May 2025, with Mehreen Faruqi continuing as deputy leader.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Sarah Hanson-Young was expected to run for the party leadership, however was elected as Manager of Greens Business.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On 6 June 2025, Senator for Western Australia Dorinda Cox defected to Labor.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Australian Greens are part of the global "green politics" movement.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Former party Leader Adam Bandt describes The Greens as a social democratic party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The charter of the Australian Greens identifies four main pillars as the party's policy: "social justice", "sustainability", "grassroots democracy" and "peace and non-violence".
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party favours environmentalism, including expansion of recycling facilities; phasing out single-use plastics; conservation efforts; and addressing species extinction, habitat loss and deforestation in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens support the achieving of 100% renewable energy by 2030 through the establishment of a Green New Deal, which entails investment in renewable energy technology and a revitalisation of Australian manufacturing.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Manufacturing would be required to produce solar panels, wind turbines and green steel produced from hydrogen.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party supports the creation of a publicly owned renewable energy provider to boost renewable energy and lower household electricity prices.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] To support the transition to clean energy, the party calls for growth in lithium mining.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens have also proposed plans to boost jobs and apprenticeships in the construction of public housing units as further economic stimulus as well as to address rising homelessness in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens oppose tax cuts that solely benefit the top bracket of income earners and lead to economic inequality.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens believe that all essential services need to be adequately funded to suit community needs; and argue for the re-establishment of a publicly owned bank.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party argues for a Corporate Super-Profits Tax on major corporations, the establishment of a wealth tax on billionaires, and an end to multi-national corporation's tax avoidance.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party advocates a significant improvement of welfare policies.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] They propose solving housing shortages and homelessness through the creation of affordable social housing.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party also wants to introduce rent caps to limit growth of rental prices.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Greens also propose increase in all income support payments to $88 a day, that would make them $1,232 per fortnight.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] To help students, the party wants to forgive all student debt.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens also advocate for free childcare as well as free public transport.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Finally, the Greens propose to increase the minimum wage.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Green politicians have campaigned on free university and technical and further education.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party opposes fee hikes for degrees and funding cuts for universities, and have called for increased funding for public schools.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party also supports the abolition of all student debt.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party supports universal health care through extending Medicare coverage into dental health care and mental health care.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Furthermore, the party supports reproductive health rights and voluntary euthanasia.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens support drug law reform, including the legalisation of cannabis; treating drug use as a health issue rather than a criminal issue; and the provision of free drug checking stations at community events and relevant venues.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Further information on the Greens cannabis legalisation proposed law can be found at Legalising Cannabis Bill 2023.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens have advocated on for various social issues, such as the legalisation of marriage equality, the right to seek asylum, and gender equality.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens also advocate for policies that they believe will strengthen Australian democracy and "clean up politics", including capping political donations and strengthening the powers of the National Anti-Corruption Commission.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In terms of agricultural policy, the party strongly favours policies to promote animal welfare and climate resilience with farmers.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens strongly support reducing soil and water degradation through community-driven decision-making processes, and supporting farmers experiencing effects of climate change.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens are in favour of phasing out live animal exports, instead favouring investment in the domestic chilled meat industry.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens have also campaigned on banning greyhound racing, whaling and animal-tested cosmetics.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party believes in phasing out caged egg production and sow stalls, instead favouring ethical farming practices.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party advocates for the reduction of methane emissions from livestock through research, animal health and nutrition, selection and genetics.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In August 2025, the Greens urged the Albanese government to impose direct sanctions on high-ranking members of Netanyahu's government and to stop supplying parts for F-35 fighter jets to the global supply chain that can be accessed by Israel.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The party supports proportional representation in the House of Representatives and local government.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On Saturday 12 November 2005 at the national conference in Hobart, the Australian Greens abandoned their long-standing tradition of having no official leader and approved a process whereby a parliamentary leader could be elected by the Greens Parliamentary Party Room.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] On Monday 28 November 2005, Bob Brown – who had long been regarded as *de facto* leader by many inside the party, and most people outside the party – was elected unopposed as the Parliamentary Party Leader.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Each leader has been described to represent a faction within the party, with the political journalist Paddy Manning describing that Christine Milne came from the right wing of the party, while Bandt is the first Greens leader from the left wing of the party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The leadership is decided by consensus within the party room (or a party room vote if consensus cannot be reached), and all previous Greens leaders have been elected unopposed (as of 2025).
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In May 2020, 62% of rank-and-file Greens party members voted for democratically Leadership election to pick the leader, However it failed to meet the two-thirds majority of 66.67% which is required to force a change.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Greens MPs are each assigned their own portfolios, or specific areas of responsibility.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] All portfolios are decided by the party and may differ in title from the government's portfolio priorities The Greens have formed a Gun Control portfolio, of which there is no equivalent in the government.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Portfolios are divided into five major categories according to the Greens: "an equal society", "world-class essential services", "climate and the environment", "the green economy", and "a confident Australia".
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Australian Greens is federally organised with separately registered state parties signing up to a national constitution, yet retaining considerable policy-making and organisational autonomy from the centre.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] As at May 2020, all seven of the party's office bearer positions are held by women.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] There is also a Public Officer, a Party Agent and a Registered Officer.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The National Council arrives at decisions by consensus.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] All policies originating from this structure are subject to ratification by the members of the Australian Greens at National Conference.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Australian Greens are a federation consisting of eight parties from each state and territory.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The various Australian states and territories have different electoral systems, all of which allow the Greens to gain representation.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] As of 2024, the Greens hold at least one seat in all eight state and territory legislatures.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Five Greens have become ministers at the state/territory level: Nick McKim and Cassy O'Connor in Tasmania, 2010–2014; and in the ACT, Shane Rattenbury since 2012 and Emma Davidson and Rebecca Vassarotti since 2020.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Most of the state-based Green parties which have joined the Australian Greens do not have a formal leader, and instead they have a shared leadership structure.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] However, Tasmania, Victoria, Western Australia, and the ACT have adopted singular leadership structures into their party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] A variety of working groups have been established by the National Council, which are directly accessible to all Greens members.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Working groups perform an advisory function by developing policy, reviewing or developing the party structure, or by performing other tasks assigned by the National Council.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Australian Young Greens are a federation of Young Greens groups from each Australian state and territory.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens generally draw support from younger voters with higher than average educational attainment.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] The Greens absorbed much of the Australian Democrats' support base following its downfall as the third party in Australia and many of the social and environmental policies and issues that the Democrats advocated for have been taken up by the Greens.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Much like the Democrats, the Greens have a higher proportion of supporters who are university educated, under 40, identify as professionals in their field, are small business owners, and earn above the national average wage.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Notably, there has also been a steady increase in working-class support for the Greens since the creation of the party.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] In 2019, Ian McAllister in an analysis of class voting patterns found that Greens voters are distinguished as being high in cultural capital, such as a university education, but tend to be in asset poverty due to not owning their own home.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Senators Vallentine, Chamarette and Margetts were all elected as Greens (WA) senators and served their terms before the Greens WA affiliated to the Australian Greens, meaning that they were not considered to be Australian Greens senators at the time.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] For current and former state parliamentarians, see the List of Australian Greens parliamentarians.
[src:harmony-day/australian-greens] Since 2017, the Australian Greens have implemented real-time disclosure of donations to them of over $1,000, in an effort to "clean up politics".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] It has been criticised for being purely a celebration of multiculturalism in Australia, with no public acknowledgement of its roots, being a commemoration of the Sharpeville massacre in 1960 in South Africa, nor acknowledgement of the existence of racism in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] On 21 March 1960, police in South Africa gunned down 69 unarmed Black South African people protesting against the pass laws in an event that became known as the Sharpeville massacre.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Six years later, the United Nations created the International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination on that date.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] This day is commemorated in most of the world apart from Australia, and remembered as a day of mourning in South Africa.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] The day was introduced by the Howard government in 1999 to promote a singular and unifying notion of "Australian-ness" within multicultural policy.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Among the conclusions of the study were that there was a need for an anti-racism campaign and a promotion of "living in harmony".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] According to multiple media reports, the outcomes of the research were not aligned with Howard's views that Australians were not racist.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Commenting on the racially motivated 2005 Cronulla riots, he stated: "I do not accept that there is underlying racism in this country".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] The Eureka report was suppressed from public access until 2011.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] In 2003, the Government of Western Australia renamed the event Harmony Day in that state, always celebrated on the same day: "celebrations from 15 to 20 March, followed by a day of reflection on 21 March".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] The event was renamed Harmony Week by the Morrison government for its 20th anniversary in 2019, "to recognise diversity and inclusion activities that take place during the entire week".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] The Department of Home Affairs leads national celebrations for Harmony Week to recognise diversity and inclusion activities that take place during the entire week.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Harmony Week is celebrated during the week (Monday to Sunday) that includes 21 March, which is the United Nations International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Since 1999, more than 80,000 Harmony Week events have been held in childcare centres, schools, community groups, churches, businesses and federal, state and local government agencies across Australia.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Harmony Day (or Week) in Australia is regarded as a celebration, with few people aware of its origins.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] It is represented by the colour orange, which "signifies social communication and meaningful conversations... [and] relates to the freedom of ideas and encouragement of mutual respect".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Criticism of Harmony Day has focused on the multicultural aspect of the day and the shift in focus away from anti-racism.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Emeritus professor Andrew Jakubowicz was critical of the 13-year governmental suppression of the original Eureka study, and the subsequent lack of research or focus on attempts to eliminate racism.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Indigenous critics like Indigenous X CEO and founder Luke Pearson argue that while Harmony Day is perceived as a positive contribution to a multicultural society, the day does little to provide practical solutions to racial discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Academic Christina Ho of the University of Technology Sydney says that Harmony Day does not deal with confronting aspects of racism such as police brutality, Aboriginal deaths in custody, and other forms of discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] She said that the choice of the word "harmony" in the name was "intentionally ideological... [by a] very socially conservative government that didn't want to acknowledge racism, didn't want to say sorry to Indigenous people".
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Anti-racism groups have highlighted media reports at the time Harmony Day was introduced arguing that the Australian government was not doing enough to eliminate racism.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] Not-for-profit group All Together Now has questioned why Harmony Day was needed at all if there was no racism in Australia.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] The Secretary for the New South Wales Fabians, a left-wing think tank, argued that the day dilutes the UN marked event of its intended meaning, and that it avoids discussion of the structural barriers of racial discrimination.
[src:harmony-day/harmony-day] In March 2023, Australian Greens senator Mehreen Faruqi wrote to Multicultural Affairs Minister Andrew Giles, saying that the government should revert to the original "name purpose and approach" of the day and that the current celebration "whitewashes this historic and ongoing racism in Australia".
